{"title_page": "Glaphyra (hetaera)", "text_new": "{{short description|Hetera}}\n'''Glaphyra''' ({{lang-el| \u0393\u03bb\u03b1\u03c6\u03cd\u03c1\u03b1}}) was a [[hetaera]],<ref>Syme, ''Anatolica: studies in Strabo'' p. 144</ref> a form of [[courtesan]], who lived in the 1st century BC. Glaphyra was famed and celebrated in antiquity for her beauty, charm and seductiveness.<ref>Syme, ''Anatolica: studies in Strabo'' pp. 144 & 148</ref> Her marriage to [[Archelaus (father of Archelaus of Cappadocia)|Archelaus the elder]] of Cappadocia gave her political power. Her later affair with [[Mark Antony]] occasioned a vulgar poem from [[Augustus|Octavian Caesar]].\n\n==Marriage to Archelaus ==\nGlaphyra was a [[Greeks|Greek woman]] from [[Cappadocia]] <ref>Watkins, ''A Biographical, Historical and Chronological Dictionary'', article on Glaphyra</ref> from obscure origins. Glaphyra had married a Cappadocian Greek nobleman called [[Archelaus (father of Archelaus of Cappadocia)|Archelaus]], the High Priest Ruler of the temple state of [[Comana (Cappadocia)|Comana, Cappadocia]].<ref name=\"ancientlibrary1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ancientlibrary.com/smith-bio/0272.html |title=Smith, Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology  |accessdate=2011-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012091837/http://www.ancientlibrary.com/smith-bio/0272.html |archivedate=2012-10-12 }} </ref> Archelaus was the High Priest of the [[Bellona (goddess)|Roman Goddess of War, Bellona]]. Through her marriage to Archelaus, Glaphyra became a ruler of the temple state. Archelaus' father of the [[Archelaus (high priest of Comana Cappadocia)|same name]] had descended from King [[Mithridates VI of Pontus]].<ref name=\"tyndalehouse1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tyndalehouse.com/egypt/ptolemies/berenice_iv.htm |title=Berenice IV |website=Tyndalehouse.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref> \n\nGlaphyra bore Archelaus two sons:\n* Archelaus Sisines,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/32710/Archelaus |title=Archelaus &#124; king of Cappadocia |website=Britannica.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref> also known as King [[Archelaus of Cappadocia]] who reigned from 36 BC until his death in 17 AD <ref>Dueck, ''Strabo\u2019s cultural geography: the making of a kolossourgia'' p. 208</ref>\n* Sisines <ref>Dueck, ''Strabo\u2019s Cultural Geography: the making of a kolossourgia'' p. 208</ref>\n\nIn 47 BC the [[Roman Dictator]] [[Julius Caesar|Gaius Julius Caesar]] after the conclusion [[Caesar's Civil War|of his military victory]] against the [[First Triumvirate|Triumvir]] [[Pompey]], deprived and deposed Archelaus of his office of high priest and rule over Comana.<ref name=\"ancientlibrary1\"/> Archelaus was replaced by another Greek nobleman called [[Lycomedes of Comana|Lycomedes]].<ref>Dueck, ''Strabo\u2019s cultural geography: the making of a kolossourgia'' p. 197</ref> Pompey was their family patron <ref>Syme, ''Anatolica: studies in Strabo'' p. 167</ref> and it was he who appointed his father as High Priest Ruler of the temple state of [[Comana (Cappadocia)|Comana]].<ref name=\"ancientlibrary1\"/> Sometime later Archelaus died at an unknown date. After the death of Archelaus, Glaphyra remained in Cappadocia with her sons. Glaphyra could be seen as the widow of the dynast of Comana.<ref>Syme, ''Anatolica: studies in Strabo'' p. 144</ref>\n\n==Affair with Antony==\nYears later, Glaphyra became one of the mistresses to the [[Second Triumvirate|Roman Triumvir]] [[Mark Antony]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tyndalehouse.com/Egypt/ptolemies/Cleopatra_vii.htm |title=Cleopatra VII |website=Tyndalehouse.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref> Through her efforts, Glaphyra had influenced and induced Antony to designate and install her first son as King of Cappadocia.<ref>Syme, ''Anatolica: studies in Strabo'' p. 148</ref> In 36 BC, Antony removed and executed [[Ariarathes X of Cappadocia]] from his throne and installed Archelaus as the successor of Ariarathes X.\n\nGlaphyra appeared to be a powerful lady at the Royal Court and was involved in internal politics in Cappadocia.<ref>Syme, ''Anatolica: studies in Strabo'' p. 148</ref> Her powerful influence can be demonstrated by contemporary invective about the time of the [[Perusine War]] in 41 BC, by certain frank and famous verses which [[Augustus|Triumvir Octavian]] composed about Antony.<ref>''Augustus: From Revolutionary to Emperor''; by Adrian Goldsworthy</ref> Antony had fallen in love with her. Octavian wrote a vulgar squib about the affair, referring to Antony's wife [[Fulvia]]: \n\n::\"Because Antony fucks Glaphyra, Fulvia has arranged\n::this punishment for me: that I fuck her too.\n::That I fuck Fulvia? What if Manius begged me\n::to bugger him? Would I? I don't think so, if I were sane.\n::'Either fuck or let's fight,' she says. Doesn't she know\n::my prick is dearer to me than life itself? Let the trumpets blare!\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GQZB28EegT4C&pg=PA99&lpg=PA99&dq=fulvia+epigram&source=bl&ots=0l3MsGRrHy&sig=AYQK_6H5D6RdcrwIZQLdhIztAcY&hl=en&ei=xdMHS4rxIpaysAO_qZTEBw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CBsQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=fulvia%20epigram&f=false |title=Cleopatra: A Sourcebook |author=Prudence J. Jones |page=99 |website=Books.google.ca |date= |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref>\n\nOriginal Latin: \n:Quod futuit Glaphyran Antonius, hanc mihi poenam\n:Fulvia constituit, se quoque uti futuam.\n:Fulvia ego ut futuam? Quid si me Manius oret\n:pedicem, faciam? Non puto, si sapiam.\n:\"Aut futue, aut pugnemus\" ait. Quid quod mihi vita\n:carior est ipsa mentula? Signa canant!\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.ancientlibrary.com/smith-bio/1380.html |title=Smith, Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology  |accessdate=2011-02-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101221074124/http://www.ancientlibrary.com/smith-bio/1380.html |archivedate=2010-12-21 }} \n*{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/32710/Archelaus |title=Archelaus &#124; king of Cappadocia |website=Britannica.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-29}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.tyndalehouse.com/Egypt/ptolemies/Cleopatra_vii.htm |title=Cleopatra VII |website=Tyndalehouse.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-29}}\n* [[John Watkins (writer)|J. Watkins]], ''A biographical, historical and chronological dictionary: containing accurate accounts of the lives, characters, and actions, of the most eminent persons of all ages and all countries: including the revolutions of states, and the succession of sovereign princes'' (Google eBook), Printed by R. Phillips by T. Gillet, 1807\n* [[George Crabb (writer)|G. Crabb]], ''Universal historical dictionary: or explanation of the names of persons and places in the departments of biblical, political and eccles. history, mythology, heraldry, biography, bibliography, geography, and numismatics'', Volume 1, Baldwin and Cradock, 1833\n* R. Syme and A.R. Birley, Anatolica: studies in Strabo, Oxford University Press, 1995\n* D. Dueck, H. Lindsay and S. Pothecary, Strabo's cultural geography: the making of a kolossourgia, Cambridge University Press, 2005\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Glaphyra (hetaera)}}\n[[Category:Hetairai]]\n[[Category:Anatolian Greeks]]\n[[Category:1st-century BC Greek women]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Hetera}}\n'''Glaphyra''' ({{lang-el| \u0393\u03bb\u03b1\u03c6\u03cd\u03c1\u03b1}}) was a [[hetaera]],<ref>Syme, ''Anatolica: studies in Strabo'' p. 144</ref> a form of [[courtesan]], who lived in the 1st century BC. Glaphyra was famed and celebrated in antiquity for her beauty, charm and seductiveness.<ref>Syme, ''Anatolica: studies in Strabo'' pp. 144 & 148</ref> Her marriage to [[Archelaus (father of Archelaus of Cappadocia)|Archelaus the elder]] of Cappadocia gave her political power. Her later affair with [[Mark Antony]] occasioned a vulgar poem from [[Augustus|Octavian Caesar]].\n\n==Marriage to Archelaus ==\nGlaphyra was a [[Greeks|Greek woman]] from [[Cappadocia]] <ref>Watkins, ''A Biographical, Historical and Chronological Dictionary'', article on Glaphyra</ref> from obscure origins. Glaphyra had married a Cappadocian Greek nobleman called [[Archelaus (father of Archelaus of Cappadocia)|Archelaus]], the High Priest Ruler of the temple state of [[Comana (Cappadocia)|Comana, Cappadocia]].<ref name=\"ancientlibrary1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ancientlibrary.com/smith-bio/0272.html |title=Smith, Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology  |accessdate=2011-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012091837/http://www.ancientlibrary.com/smith-bio/0272.html |archivedate=2012-10-12 }} </ref> Archelaus was the High Priest of the [[Bellona (goddess)|Roman Goddess of War, Bellona]]. Through her marriage to Archelaus, Glaphyra became a ruler of the temple state. Archelaus' father of the [[Archelaus (high priest of Comana Cappadocia)|same name]] had descended from King [[Mithridates VI of Pontus]].<ref name=\"tyndalehouse1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tyndalehouse.com/egypt/ptolemies/berenice_iv.htm |title=Berenice IV |website=Tyndalehouse.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref> \n\nGlaphyra bore Archelaus two sons:\n* Archelaus Sisines,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/32710/Archelaus |title=Archelaus &#124; king of Cappadocia |website=Britannica.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref> also known as King [[Archelaus of Cappadocia]] who reigned from 36 BC until his death in 17 AD <ref>Dueck, ''Strabo\u2019s cultural geography: the making of a kolossourgia'' p. 208</ref>\n* Sisines <ref>Dueck, ''Strabo\u2019s Cultural Geography: the making of a kolossourgia'' p. 208</ref>\n\nIn 47 BC the [[Roman Dictator]] [[Julius Caesar|Gaius Julius Caesar]] after the conclusion [[Caesar's Civil War|of his military victory]] against the [[First Triumvirate|Triumvir]] [[Pompey]], deprived and deposed Archelaus of his office of high priest and rule over Comana.<ref name=\"ancientlibrary1\"/> Archelaus was replaced by another Greek nobleman called [[Lycomedes of Comana|Lycomedes]].<ref>Dueck, ''Strabo\u2019s cultural geography: the making of a kolossourgia'' p. 197</ref> Pompey was their family patron <ref>Syme, ''Anatolica: studies in Strabo'' p. 167</ref> and it was he who appointed his father as High Priest Ruler of the temple state of [[Comana (Cappadocia)|Comana]].<ref name=\"ancientlibrary1\"/> Sometime later Archelaus died at an unknown date. After the death of Archelaus, Glaphyra remained in Cappadocia with her sons. Glaphyra could be seen as the widow of the dynast of Comana.<ref>Syme, ''Anatolica: studies in Strabo'' p. 144</ref>\n\n==Affair with Antony==\nYears later, Glaphyra became one of the mistresses to the [[Second Triumvirate|Roman Triumvir]] [[Mark Antony]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tyndalehouse.com/Egypt/ptolemies/Cleopatra_vii.htm |title=Cleopatra VII |website=Tyndalehouse.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref> Through her efforts, Glaphyra had influenced and induced Antony to designate and install her first son as King of Cappadocia.<ref>Syme, ''Anatolica: studies in Strabo'' p. 148</ref> In 36 BC, Antony removed and executed [[Ariarathes X of Cappadocia]] from his throne and installed Archelaus as the successor of Ariarathes X.\n\nGlaphyra appeared to be a powerful lady at the Royal Court and was involved in internal politics in Cappadocia.<ref>Syme, ''Anatolica: studies in Strabo'' p. 148</ref> Her powerful influence can be demonstrated by contemporary invective about the time of the [[Perusine War]] in 41 BC, by certain frank and famous verses which [[Augustus|Triumvir Octavian]] composed about Antony.<ref>''Augustus: From Revolutionary to Emperor''; by Adrian Goldsworthy</ref> Antony had fallen in love with her. Octavian wrote a vulgar squib about the affair, referring to Antony's wife [[Fulvia]]: \n\n::\"Because Antony fucks Glaphyra, Fulvia has arranged\n::this punishment for me: that I fuck her too.\n::That I fuck Fulvia? What if Manius begged me\n::to bugger him? Would I? I don't think so, if I were sane.\n::'Either fuck or let's fight,' she says. Doesn't she know\n::my prick is dearer to me than life itself? Let the trumpets blare!\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GQZB28EegT4C&pg=PA99&lpg=PA99&dq=fulvia+epigram&source=bl&ots=0l3MsGRrHy&sig=AYQK_6H5D6RdcrwIZQLdhIztAcY&hl=en&ei=xdMHS4rxIpaysAO_qZTEBw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CBsQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=fulvia%20epigram&f=false |title=Cleopatra: A Sourcebook |author=Prudence J. Jones |page=99 |website=Books.google.ca |date= |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref>\n\nOriginal Latin: \n:Quod futuit Glaphyran Antonius, hanc mihi poenam\n:Fulvia constituit, se quoque uti futuam.\n:Fulvia ego ut futuam? Quid si me Manius oret\n:pedicem, faciam? Non puto, si sapiam.\n:\"Aut futue, aut pugnemus\" ait. Quid quod mihi vita\n:carior est ipsa mentula? Signa canant!\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.ancientlibrary.com/smith-bio/1380.html |title=Smith, Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology  |accessdate=2011-02-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101221074124/http://www.ancientlibrary.com/smith-bio/1380.html |archivedate=2010-12-21 }} \n*{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/32710/Archelaus |title=Archelaus &#124; king of Cappadocia |website=Britannica.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-29}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.tyndalehouse.com/Egypt/ptolemies/Cleopatra_vii.htm |title=Cleopatra VII |website=Tyndalehouse.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-29}}\n* [[John Watkins (writer)|J. Watkins]], ''A biographical, historical and chronological dictionary: containing accurate accounts of the lives, characters, and actions, of the most eminent persons of all ages and all countries: including the revolutions of states, and the succession of