{"title_page": "Yuval Levin", "text_new": "{{short description|Israeli-American political analyst and journalist}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Yuval Levin\n|image         = Yuval Levin AEI 1-Oct-2015.jpg\n|alt           = A man with close-cropped, receding hair, wearing a suite, looking intently slightly to his right. He is sitting at a table with a microphone against a blue, repeating ARI logo.\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1977|4|6}}\n|birth_place   = [[Haifa]], [[Israel]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|education     = [[American University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br />[[University of Chicago]] {{small|([[Master of Arts|MA]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])}}\n|notable_works = ''The Great Debate: Edmund Burke, Thomas Paine, and the Birth of Left and Right'' (2013)\n}}\n'''Yuval Levin''' (born April 6, 1977)<ref>{{Citation | title = Yuval Levin | work = Good reads | publisher = Amazon | URL = https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/2739781.Yuval_Levin}}.</ref> is an American [[political analyst]], [[public intellectual]], [[academic]], and [[journalist]]. He is the founding editor of ''[[National Affairs]]'' (2009\u2013present), director of Social, Cultural, and Constitutional Studies at the [[American Enterprise Institute]]<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.aei.org/profile/yuval-levin/ |title=Yuval Levin|website=American Enterprise Institute - AEI|language= en-US |access-date=2019-09-28}}</ref> (2019\u2013present), a contributing editor of ''[[National Review]]'' (2007\u2013present) and co-founder and a senior editor of ''[[The New Atlantis (journal)|The New Atlantis]]'' (2003\u2013present)''.'' \n\nLevin was vice president and Hertog Fellow of [[Ethics and Public Policy Center]] (2007\u201319), executive director of the [[President's Council on Bioethics]] (2001\u201304), Special Assistant to the President for Domestic Policy (2004\u201307) and contributing editor to [[The Weekly Standard]] (1995\u20132018). Prior to that he served as a congressional staffer at the member, committee, and leadership levels.\n\nLevin's essays and articles have appeared in numerous publications including  ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', ''[[Commentary (magazine)|Commentary]]'', and others. He is the author of several books on political theory and public policy, including \u201cThe Fractured Republic: Renewing America\u2019s Social Contract in the Age of Individualism\u201d (Basic Books, 2016). In 2020, he published his latest book, \u201cA Time to Build: From Family and Community to Congress and the Campus, How Recommitting to Our Institutions Can Revive the American Dream\u201d (Basic Books).\n\n==Early life and education==\nLevin was born in [[Haifa]], [[Israel]], and moved to the [[United States]] with his family at the age of eight.<ref name=\"babykristol\">{{cite news |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/112745/yuval-levin-rights-new-irving-kristol |title=Baby Kristol |last=Tracy |first=Mark |work=[[The New Republic]] |date=March 25, 2013 |accessdate=February 9, 2017}}</ref> He earned a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[political science]] at [[American University]], and earned a PhD from the [[Committee on Social Thought]] at the [[University of Chicago]].\n\n==Career==\nLevin is the author of four books, and of numerous essays and articles dealing largely with [[political theory]], [[science]], [[technology]], and [[Policy|public policy]]. On the relationship between political theory and public policy, Levin has said:\n\n<blockquote>For me, these things are very deeply connected. I think politics really is rooted in political philosophy, is much better understood when it's understood in light of political philosophy. And that a lot of the policy debates we have make much more sense if you see that people are arguing about two ways of understanding what the human person is, what human society is, and especially what the liberal society is. The left and right in our country are both liberal, they both believe in the free society, but they mean something very different by that.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Levin|first1=Yuval|title=Conversations with Bill Kristol|url=http://conversationswithbillkristol.org/video/yuval-levin-2/|website=Conversations with Bill Kristol|accessdate=1 October 2014}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nConservatism, Levin has said, \"understands society not as just individuals and government, but thinks of it in terms of everything that happens in between. That huge space between the individual and the state is where society actually is. And that's where families are, it's where communities are, it's where the market economy is.\" <ref>{{cite web|last1=Levin|first1=Yuval|title=Conversations with Bill Kristol (transcript)|url=https://conversationswithbillkristol.org/transcript/yuval-levin-transcript/|website=Conversations with Bill Kristol|accessdate=1 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nLevin has been called \"probably the most influential conservative intellectual of the Obama era\",<ref>{{cite web|last=Chait|first=Jonathan|title=The Facts Are In and Paul Ryan Is Wrong|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2013/05/facts-are-in-and-paul-ryan-is-wrong.html|work=New York|accessdate=10 May 2013}}</ref> while ''[[The New Republic]]'' has dubbed Levin \"the right's new [[Irving Kristol]]\".<ref name=\"babykristol\" />\n\n==Works==\n*{{cite book|last1=Levin|first1=Yuval|title= Tyranny of Reason: The Origins and Consequences of the Social Scientific Outlook|date= 2001 |publisher= University Press of America|location= Lanham, [[Maryland | MD]] |isbn= 978-0-76181872-4|oclc=45087346}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Levin|first1=Yuval|title=Imagining the Future: Science and American Democracy|date= 2008 |publisher= Encounter Books |location= New York|isbn= 978-1-59403330-8|oclc= 503444967}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yuval|first1=Levin|title=The Great Debate: Edmund Burke, Thomas Paine, and the Birth of Right and Left |date=2014|publisher=Basic Books|location= New York|isbn= 978-0-46505097-0 |oclc=858672374}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yuval|first1=Levin|title=The Fractured Republic: Renewing America's Social Contract in the Age of Individualism|date=2016 |publisher= Basic Books|location=New York|isbn= 978-0-46506196-9 |oclc=945121355}}\n*''[[A Time to Build]]'': From Family and Community to Congress and the Campus, How Recommitting to Our Institutions Can Revive the American Dream (2020, Basic Books)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090912124831/http://www.nationalaffairs.com/authors/detail/yuval-levin Levin's biography on the ''National Affairs'' website]\n* [http://www.nationalreview.com/author/yuval-levin Levin's ''National Review'' archive]\n* [http://www.weeklystandard.com/author/yuval-levin Levin's ''Weekly Standard'' archive]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130610065255/http://www.thenewatlantis.com/authors/yuval-levin Partially comprehensive publications list at ''The New Atlantis'']\n* [http://www.econtalk.org/archives/2016/07/yuval_levin_on_1.html Discussion regarding ''The Fractured Republic''] with [[Russ Roberts]] on [[EconTalk]]\n* {{C-SPAN|yuvallevin}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Levin, Yuval}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American writers]]\n[[Category:American magazine editors]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:American political philosophers]]\n[[Category:American University School of Public Affairs alumni]]\n[[Category:Israeli emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish American academics]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Haifa]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:The Weekly Standard people]]\n[[Category:Ethics and Public Policy Center]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Israeli-American political analyst and journalist}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Yuval Levin\n|image         = Yuval Levin AEI 1-Oct-2015.jpg\n|alt           = A man with close-cropped, receding hair, wearing a suite, looking intently slightly to his right. He is sitting at a table with a microphone against a blue, repeating ARI logo.\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1977|4|6}}\n|birth_place   = [[Haifa]], [[Israel]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|education     = [[American University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br />[[University of Chicago]] {{small|([[Master of Arts|MA]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])}}\n|notable_works = ''The Great Debate: Edmund Burke, Thomas Paine, and the Birth of Left and Right'' (2013)\n}}\n'''Yuval Levin''' (born April 6, 1977)<ref>{{Citation | title = Yuval Levin | work = Good reads | publisher = Amazon | URL = https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/2739781.Yuval_Levin}}.</ref> is an American [[political analyst]], [[public intellectual]], [[academic]], and [[journalist]]. He is the founding editor of ''[[National Affairs]]'' (2009\u2013present), director of Social, Cultural, and Constitutional Studies at the [[American Enterprise Institute]]<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.aei.org/profile/yuval-levin/ |title=Yuval Levin|website=American Enterprise Institute - AEI|language= en-US |access-date=2019-09-28}}</ref> (2019\u2013present), a contributing editor of [[National Review]] (2007\u2013present) and co-founder and a senior editor of [[The New Atlantis (journal)|The New Atlantis]] (2003\u2013present)''.'' \n\nLevin was vice president and Hertog Fellow of [[Ethics and Public Policy Center]] (2007\u201319), executive director of the [[President's Council on Bioethics]] (2001\u201304), Special Assistant to the President for Domestic Policy (2004\u201307) and contributing editor to [[The Weekly Standard]] (1995\u20132018). Prior to that he served as a congressional staffer at the member, committee, and leadership levels.\n\nLevin's essays and articles have appeared in numerous publications including  ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', ''[[Commentary (magazine)|Commentary]]'', and others. He is the author of several books on political theory and public policy, including \u201cThe Fractured Republic: Renewing America\u2019s Social Contract in the Age of Individualism\u201d (Basic Books, 2016). In 2020, he published his latest book, \u201cA Time to Build: From Family and Community to Congress and the Campus, How Recommitting to Our Institutions Can Revive the American Dream\u201d (Basic Books).\n\n==Early life and education==\nLevin was born in [[Haifa]], [[Israel]], and moved to the [[United States]] with his family at the age of eight.<ref name=\"babykristol\">{{cite news |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/112745/yuval-levin-rights-new-irving-kristol |title=Baby Kristol |last=Tracy |first=Mark |work=[[The New Republic]] |date=March 25, 2013 |accessdate=February 9, 2017}}</ref> He earned a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[political science]] at [[American University]], and earned a PhD from the [[Committee on Social Thought]] at the [[University of Chicago]].\n\n==Career==\nLevin is the author of four books, and of numerous essays and articles dealing largely with [[political theory]], [[science]], [[technology]], and [[Policy|public policy]]. On the relationship between political theory and public policy, Levin has said:\n\n<blockquote>For me, these things are very deeply connected. I think politics really is rooted in political philosophy, is much better understood when it's understood in light of political philosophy. And that a lot of the policy debates we have make much more sense if you see that people are arguing about two ways of understanding what the human person is, what human society is, and especially what the liberal society is. The left and right in our country are both liberal, they both believe in the free society, but they mean something very different by that.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Levin|first1=Yuval|title=Conversations with Bill Kristol|url=http://conversationswithbillkristol.org/video/yuval-levin-2/|website=Conversations with Bill Kristol|accessdate=1 October 2014}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nConservatism, Levin has said, \"understands society not as just individuals and government, but thinks of it in terms of everything that happens in between. That huge space between the individual and the state is where society actually is. And that's where families are, it's where communities are, it's where the market economy is.\" <ref>{{cite web|last1=Levin|first1=Yuval|title=Conversations with Bill Kristol (transcript)|url=https://conversationswithbillkristol.org/transcript/yuval-levin-transcript/|website=Conversations with Bill Kristol|accessdate=1 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nLevin has been called \"probably the most influential conservative intellectual of the Obama era\",<ref>{{cite web|last=Chait|first=Jonathan|title=The Facts Are In and Paul Ryan Is Wrong|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2013/05/facts-are-in-and-paul-ryan-is-wrong.html|work=New York|accessdate=10 May 2013}}</ref> while ''[[The New Republic]]'' has dubbed Levin \"the right's new [[Irving Kristol]]\".<ref name=\"babykristol\" />\n\n==Works==\n*{{cite book|last1=Levin|first1=Yuval|title= Tyranny of Reason: The Origins and Consequences of the Social Scientific Outlook|date= 2001 |publisher= University Press of America|location= Lanham, [[Maryland | MD]] |isbn= 978-0-76181872-4|oclc=45087346}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Levin|first1=Yuval|title=Imagining the Future: Science and American Democracy|date= 2008 |publisher= Encounter Books |location= New York|isbn= 978-1-59403330-8|oclc= 503444967}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yuval|first1=Levin|title=The Great Debate: Edmund Burke, Thomas Paine, and the Birth of Right and Left |date=2014|publisher=Basic Books|location= New York|isbn= 978-0-46505097-0 |oclc=858672374}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yuval|first1=Levin|title=The Fractured Republic: Renewing America's Social Contract in the Age of Individualism|date=2016 |publisher= Basic Books|location=New York|isbn= 978-0-46506196-9 |oclc=945121355}}\n*''[[A Time to Build]]'': From Family and Community to Congress and the Campus, How Recommitting to Our Institutions Can Revive the American Dream (2020, Basic Books)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090912124831/http://www.nationalaffairs.com/authors/detail/yuval-levin Levin's biography on the ''National Affairs'' website]\n* [http://www.nationalreview.com/author/yuval-levin Levin's ''National Review'' archive]\n* [http://www.weeklystandard.com/author/yuval-levin Levin's ''Weekly Standard'' archive]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130610065255/http://www.thenewatlantis.com/authors/yuval-levin Partially comprehensive publications list at ''The New Atlantis'']\n* [http://www.econtalk.org/archives/2016/07/yuval_levin_on_1.html Discussion regarding ''The Fractured Republic''] with [[Russ Roberts]] on [[EconTalk]]\n* {{C-SPAN|yuvallevin}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Levin, Yuval}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American writers]]\n[[Category:American magazine editors]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:American political philosophers]]\n[[Category:American University School of Public Affairs alumni]]\n[[Category:Israeli emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish American academics]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Haifa]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:The Weekly Standard people]]\n[[Category:Ethics and Public Policy Center]]\n", "name_user": "Marquardtika", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yuval_Levin"}
{"title_page": "L\u00e9o L\u00e9vesque", "text_new": "'''L\u00e9o L\u00e9vesque''' is a French Canadian poet, essayist, and writer born in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]].<ref>[http://www.aqad.qc.ca/list.asp?aid=252 L\u00e9o L\u00e9vesque] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071211125416/http://www.aqad.qc.ca/list.asp?aid=252 |date=2007-12-11 }} at the Association Qu\u00e9b\u00e9coise des auteurs dramatiques</ref> He was a finalist for the [[1982 Governor General's Awards|1982]] [[Governor General's Award|Governor General's Award for Literary Merit]], and won $10,000 funding in 1997\u201398 from the [[Canada Council for the Arts]].<ref>[http://dsp-psd.pwgsc.gc.ca/Collection/K21-15-1999E.pdf Profile of Funding to Qu\u00e9bec, 1997-98], The Canada Council for the Arts</ref>\n\nHe spent 25 years in prison, and has written five collections of prison stories based on his experience, of which ''Contes en coups de poing'' was the basis of the 2002 movie ''[[Inside (2002 film)|Inside]] (Histoire de pen)''.<ref>[http://www.darkvault.ca/pdf/inside-mk.pdf ''Inside'' media kit]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Levesque, Leo}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:Canadian male poets]]\n[[Category:Writers from Montreal]]\n[[Category:French Quebecers]]\n[[Category:Canadian poets in French]]\n[[Category:Canadian male essayists]]\n[[Category:Canadian dramatists and playwrights in French]]\n[[Category:Canadian male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian male writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "'''L\u00e9o L\u00e9vesque''' is a French Canadian poet, essayist, and writer born in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]].<ref>[http://www.aqad.qc.ca/list.asp?aid=252 L\u00e9o L\u00e9vesque] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071211125416/http://www.aqad.qc.ca/list.asp?aid=252 |date=2007-12-11 }} at the Association Qu\u00e9b\u00e9coise des auteurs dramatiques</ref> He was a finalist for the [[1982 Governor General's Awards|1982]] [[Governor General's Award|Governor General's Award for Literary Merit]], and won $10,000 funding in 1997\u201398 from the [[Canada Council for the Arts]].<ref>[http://dsp-psd.pwgsc.gc.ca/Collection/K21-15-1999E.pdf Profile of Funding to Qu\u00e9bec, 1997-98], The Canada Council for the Arts</ref>\n\nHe spent 25 years in prison, and has written five collections of prison stories based on his experience, of which ''Contes en coups de poing'' was the basis of the 2002 movie ''[[Inside (2002 film)|Inside]] (Histoire de pen)''.<ref>[http://www.darkvault.ca/pdf/inside-mk.pdf ''Inside'' media kit]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Levesque, Leo}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:Canadian male poets]]\n[[Category:Writers from Montreal]]\n[[Category:French Quebecers]]\n[[Category:Canadian poets in French]]\n[[Category:Male essayists]]\n[[Category:Canadian dramatists and playwrights in French]]\n[[Category:Canadian male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian male writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L%C3%A9o_L%C3%A9vesque"}
{"title_page": "Earth Similarity Index", "text_new": "[[File:Terrestrial planet sizes.jpg|thumb|510x510px|Though differing in size and temperature, terrestrial planets of the Solar System tend to have high Earth Similarity Index values \u2013 [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]] (0.596), [[Venus]] (0.444), [[Earth]] (1.00) and [[Mars]] (0.697){{cn|date=August 2019}}. Sizes to scale.<ref name=\"UPR-Catalog\">{{Cite web|url = http://phl.upr.edu/projects/habitable-exoplanets-catalog/data|title = HEC: Data of Potential Habitable Worlds}}</ref>]]\nThe '''Earth Similarity Index''' ('''ESI''') is a proposed characterization of how similar a [[planetary-mass object]] or [[natural satellite]] is to [[Earth]].  It was designed to be a scale from zero to one, with Earth having a value of one; this is meant to simplify planet comparisons from large databases. It has no quantitative meaning for [[Planetary habitability|habitability]].\n\n== Formulation ==\nThe ESI, as proposed in 2011 by Schulze-Makuch ''et al.'' in the journal [[Astrobiology (journal)|''Astrobiology'']]'','' incorporates a planet's [[radius]], [[density]], [[escape velocity]], and [[Planetary equilibrium temperature|surface temperature]] into the index.<ref name=\"Schulze-Makuch et al.\">{{cite journal |author=Schulze-Makuch, D. |author2=M\u00e9ndez, A. |author3=Fair\u00e9n, A. G. |author4=von Paris, P. |author5=Turse, C. |author6=Boyer, G. |author7= Davila, A. F. |author8=Resendes de Sousa Ant\u00f3nio, M. |author9=Catling, D. |author10=Irwin, L. N. |last-author-amp=yes |date=2011 |doi=10.1089/ast.2010.0592 |bibcode=2011AsBio..11.1041S |title=A Two-Tiered Approach to Assess the Habitability of Exoplanets. |journal=Astrobiology |volume=11 |issue=10 |pages=1041\u20131052 |pmid=22017274}}</ref> Thus the authors describe the index as having two components: (1) associated with the interior which is associated with the mean radius and bulk density, and (2) associated with the surface which is associated with the escape velocity and surface temperature. An article on the [[preprint server]] [[arxiv.org]] attempts to reproduce the ESI using only the temperature and [[Planetary mass|mass]] of the planet.<ref name=\"Chandra\">{{cite arXiv|eprint=1507.06293v1|class=astro-ph.EP|author=Suresh Chandra|author2=Subas Nepal|title=Earth Similarity Index with two free parameters|date=July 2015|author3=Mohit K. Sharma}}<!-- pages=2-4 --></ref> ESI was also referenced in an article published in ''[[Revista Cubana de F\u00edsica]]''.<ref name=\"Gonzalez\">{{cite journal|year=2013|title=Possibilities of life around Alpha Centauri B.|arxiv=1401.2211|journal=Revista Cubana de F\u00edsica|volume=30|issue=2|page=81|author=Gonzalez, A.|author2=Cardenas, R.|author3=Hearnshaw, J.|last-author-amp=yes|bibcode = 2014arXiv1401.2211G }}</ref>\n\nFor [[exoplanet]]s, in almost every case only the planet's [[orbital period]] along with either the [[transit method|proportional dimming of the star due to the planet's transit]] or the [[radial velocity method|radial velocity variation of the star]] in response to the planet is known with any degree of certainty, and so every other property not directly determined by those measurements is speculative. For example, while surface temperature is influenced by a variety of factors including [[irradiance]], [[tidal heating]], [[albedo]], [[insolation]] and [[greenhouse warming]], as these factors are not known for any exoplanet, quoted ESI values use [[planetary equilibrium temperature]] as a stand-in.<ref name=\"Schulze-Makuch et al.\" />\n\nA webpage maintained by one of the authors of the 2011 ''Astrobiology'' article, Abel M\u00e9ndez at the [[University of Puerto Rico at Arecibo]], lists his calculations of the index for various exoplanetary systems.<ref name=esi>{{cite web|title=Earth Similarity Index (ESI)|url=http://phl.upr.edu/projects/earth-similarity-index-esi|publisher=Planetary Habitability Laboratory}}</ref> M\u00e9ndez's ESI is calculated as\n\n:<math>\\mathsf{ESI} = \\prod_{i=1}^{n}\\left(1-\\Big\\vert\\frac{x_i - x_{i0}}{x_i + x_{i0}}\\Big\\vert\\right)^\\frac{w_i}{n}</math>,\n\nwhere <math>x_i</math> and <math>x_{i0}</math> are properties of the extraterrestrial body and of Earth, respectively, <math>w_i</math> is the weighted exponent of each property, and <math>n</math> is the total number of properties. It is comparable to, and constructed from, the [[Bray\u2013Curtis dissimilarity|Bray\u2013Curtis Similarity Index]].<ref name=esi /><ref name=\"Rushby\">{{cite journal|author=Rushby, A.|year=2013|title=A multiplicity of worlds: Other habitable planets|journal=Significance|volume=10|issue=5|pages=11\u201315|doi=10.1111/j.1740-9713.2013.00690.x}}</ref> The weight assigned to each property, <math>w_i</math>, are [[free parameter]]s that can be chosen to emphasize certain characteristics over others or to obtain desired index thresholds or rankings. The webpage also ranks what it describes as the habitability of planets and moons according to three criteria: the location in the habitable zone, ESI, and a speculation as to a capacity to sustain organisms at the bottom of the food chain, a different index collated on the webpage identified as the \"Global Primary Habitability scale\".<ref name=\"Sample\">{{cite news|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2011/dec/05/habitable-exoplanets-catalogue-alien-life|title=Habitable exoplanets catalogue ranks alien worlds on suitability for life.|author=Sample, I.|date=December 5, 2011|accessdate=April 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe 2011 ''Astrobiology'' article and the ESI values found in it received press attention at the time of the article's  publication. As a result, [[Mars]] was reported to have the second-highest ESI in the Solar System with a value of 0.70.<ref name=\"BBC\" />  A number of [[exoplanet]]s listed in that article were reported to have values in excess of this, with [[Teegarden b]] reported to have the highest ESI<ref name=\"Armstrong\" /> of [[Exoplanet#Confirmed discoveries|confirmed]] exoplanets at 0.95.\n\nOther ESI values that have been reported by third parties include:<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|title=Most liveable alien worlds ranked|date=November 23, 2011|accessdate=April 10, 2016|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-15863549|publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref><ref name=esi />\n\nIn next table, planets marked with * represents unconfirmed planet or planet candidate. Distances are from Earth Star system.\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Planet || ESI || Distance ([[Light-year|ly]]) || Notes\n|-\n| Earth || {{ESIScore |esi=1.00}} || 0 ||\n|-\n|[[KOI-4878.01]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.98}} ||1075\n|unconfirmed but surface pressure may be 10[[Atmosphere_(unit)|atm]] at 292K, G4V-type Sun-like star\n|-\n|[[TRAPPIST-1e]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.95}} || 40 ||likely [[Tidal locking|tidally locked]] to star, surface pressure may be as little as 6[[Atmosphere_(unit)|atm]] at 285K, one of the most habitable known planets\n|-\n|[[Teegarden b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.95}} || 12 ||\n|-\n|[[Gliese 581 g]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.92}} || 20 ||unconfirmed, [[Tidal locking|tidally locked]] to star, surface pressure may be 18[[Atmosphere_(unit)|atm]] at 284K\n|-\n|[[Luyten b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.91}} || 12.2 ||[[Tidal locking|tidally locked]] to star, surface pressure may be 25[[Atmosphere_(unit)|atm]] at 294K\n|-\n|[[TRAPPIST-1 d]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.91}} || 40 ||innermost habitable planet in TRAPPIST-1 system\n|-\n|[[Kepler-438b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.88}} || 640 ||temperature 276 K, likely [[Tidal locking|tidally locked]], habitability is uncertain\n|-\n|[[Proxima Centauri b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.87}} || 4.2 ||closest potentially habitable planet\n|-\n|[[Ross 128 b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.86}} || 11 ||host star is inactive and quiet, it is habitable if has an Earth-like atmosphere\n|-\n|[[LHS 1723|LHS 1723 b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.86}} || 17.5 ||lack of planet density or atmospheric data \n|-\n|[[Kepler-296 e]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.85}} || ||\n|-\n|[[Gliese 667 Cc]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.85}} || 23.62 ||likely [[Tidal locking|tidally locked]]  to star, temperature is 277.4 K (4.3\u00b0C), based on black body temperature calculation\n|-\n|[[Kepler-442b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.84}} || 1206 ||it is in center of the habitable zone, temperature 233 K\n|-\n|[[Kepler-452b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.83}} || 1402 ||surface pressure may be 16-56[[Atmosphere_(unit)|atm]] at 288K with [[Breathing gas|Helium]] if strong [[Absorption spectroscopy|587.5nm line]].\n|- \n|[[Kepler-62e]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.83}} || 1200 ||surface pressure may be 35[[Atmosphere_(unit)|atm]] at 288K with [[Breathing gas|Helium]] if strong [[Absorption spectroscopy|587.5nm line]].\n|-  \n|[[Gliese 832 c]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.81}} || 16 ||[[Tidal locking|tidally locked]], no [[plate tectonics]], it is habitable if have an Earth-like atmosphere \n|-\n|[[Kepler-283c]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.79}} || ||temperature is 238.5 K\n|-\n|[[HD 85512 b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.77}} || 36 || if has an Earth-like atmosphere, without [[greenhouse effect]]\n|-\n|[[Wolf 1061c]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.76}} || 13.8 || \n|-\n|[[Gliese 667 Cf]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.76}} || 23.6 ||controversial existence\n|-\n|[[Kepler-440b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.75}} || 850 ||it has an elliptical orbit, temperature 273 K \n|-\n|[[HD 40307 g]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.74}} || 42 ||  \n|-\n|[[Mars]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.73}} ||  ||lacks global [[plate tectonics]], too small for [[Atmospheric escape|atmospheric water vapour]]\n|-\n|[[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.73}} || ||in 3:2 [[Orbital resonance|spin-orbital resonance]] to [[Sun]]\n|-\n|[[Kepler-61b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.73}} || 1100 || \n|-\n|[[K2-18b]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.73}} || 124 ||temperature is 265 K, also known as EPIC 201912552 b\n|-\n|[[Gliese 581 d]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.72}} || 20.4 ||[[Tidal locking|tidally locked]] to star\n|-\n|[[Kepler-22b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.71}} || 587 ||  \n|-\n|[[Kepler-443b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.71}} || 2540 ||it has 89.9% chance of habitability, yet only 4.3% to be rocky\n|-\n|[[Gliese 422 b]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.71}} || ||unconfirmed\n|-\n|[[TRAPPIST-1 f]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.70}} || 39 ||temperature is 230 K, small chance to be rocky\n|-\n|[[Gliese 3293 c]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.70}} || ||unconfirmed\n|-\n|[[Kepler-62f]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.69}} || 990 ||surface pressure may be 10[[Atmosphere_(unit)|atm]] at 288K with [[Breathing gas|Helium]] if strong [[Absorption spectroscopy|587.5nm line]]\n|-\n|[[Teegarden c]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.68}} || 12 ||  \n|-\n|[[Kepler-298d]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.68}} || 1545 ||  \n|-\n|[[Kapteyn b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.67}} || 12.8 ||oldest known potentially habitable planet \n|-\n|[[Kepler-186f]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.64}} || 582 ||potentially colder climate than Mars, but still habitable planet\n|-\n|[[Kepler-174d]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.61}} || \n|-\n|[[Kepler-296f]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.60}} || \n|-\n|[[Gliese 667 Ce]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.60}} || 23.6 ||controversial existence\n|-\n|[[HD 69830 d]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.60}} || 40.7 ||lack of planet density or atmospheric data\n|-\n|[[TRAPPIST-1 g]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.59}} || 39 ||largest planet in system, too cold to be habitable \n|-\n|[[Gliese 682 c]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.59}} ||  ||unconfirmed \n|-\n|[[55 Cancri c|55 Cnc c]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.56}} ||  ||lack of planet density or atmospheric data\n|-\n|[[Moon]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.56}} ||  ||too small for surface or [[Atmospheric escape|atmospheric water]], lacks [[plate tectonics]]\n|-\n|[[55 Cancri f|55 Cnc f]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.53}} || 41 ||lack of planet density or atmospheric data\n|-\n|[[KOI-4427b]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.52}} ||  ||unconfirmed\n|-\n|[[Gliese 581b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.48}} || ||it orbits within inner edge of habitable zone\n|-\n|[[Venus]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.44}} || ||solar [[Radiant flux|flux]] > [[Komabayasi-Ingersoll limit]], [[Retrograde and prograde motion|slow retrograde orbit]] induced by [[Sun]].\n|-\n|[[Kepler-20f]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.44}} || 929 || \n|-\n|[[Gliese 1214b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.42}} || 48 ||it is probably ocean planet, temperature 390-552 K\n|-\n|[[Kepler-11b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.30}} || || \n|-\n|[[Kepler-20e]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.29}} || || \n|-\n|[[Mu Arae e]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.27}} || || \n|-\n|[[Gliese 581 c]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.24}} || 20.37 ||[[Tidal locking|tidally locked]] to star\n|-\n|[[Kepler-20b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.24}} || || \n|-\n|[[Neptune (planet)|Neptune]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.18}} || ||Gas giant, blue color\n|-\n|[[Gliese 581 e]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.16}} || 20.4 ||[[Tidal locking|tidally locked]] to star\n|-\n|[[Jupiter (planet)|Jupiter]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.12}} || ||Gas giant\n|-\n|[[KOI-55c]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.03}} || || \n|-\n|}\n\n==No relation to habitability==\nAlthough the ESI does not characterize [[planetary habitability|habitability]], given the point of reference is the Earth, some of its functions match those used by habitability measures. As with the definition of the [[habitable zone]], the ESI uses surface temperature as a primary function (and the terrestrial point of reference).  A 2016 article uses ESI as a target selection scheme and obtains results showing that the ESI has little relation to the habitability of an exoplanet, as it takes no account of the [[Flare star|activity of the star]], planetary [[tidal locking]], nor the planet's [[magnetosphere|magnetic field]] (i.e. ability to protect itself) which are among the keys to habitable surface conditions.<ref name=\"Armstrong\">{{cite journal |title=The host stars of Kepler's habitable exoplanets: superflares, rotation and activity |author=Armstrong, D. J. |author2=Pugh, C. E. |author3=Broomhall, A.-M. |author4=Brown, D. J. A. |author5=Lund, M. N. |author6=Osborn, H. P. |author7=Pollacco, D. L. |journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society |volume=5 |issue=3 |year=2016 |doi=10.1093/mnras/stv2419 |bibcode=2016MNRAS.455.3110A |arxiv=1511.05306 |pages=3110\u20133125}}</ref>\n\nIt has been noted that ESI fails to differentiate between [[Earth]] similarity and [[Venus]] similarity, as can be seen in the table above, where planets with a lower ESI have a greater chance at habitability<ref name=\"Tasker\">{{cite news|title=No, that new exoplanet is not the best candidate to support life|url=https://theconversation.com/no-that-new-exoplanet-is-not-the-best-candidate-to-support-life-28996|author=Elizabeth Tasker|date=July 9, 2014|publisher=[[The Conversation]]|accessdate=November 5, 2018}}</ref>.\n\n==Planets with an Earth-like size==\n\n[[File:Relative sizes of all of the habitable-zone planets discovered to date alongside Earth.jpg|thumb|Comparison of the sizes of planets [[Kepler-69c]], [[Kepler-62e]] (0.83), [[Kepler-62f]] (0.69), and the [[Earth]]. All planets except the Earth are artists' conceptions.]] \nThe classification of exoplanets is difficult in that many methods of exoplanet detection leave several features unknown. For example, with the [[transit method]], one of the more successful measurement of radius can be highly accurate, but mass and density are often estimated. Likewise with [[radial velocity]] methods, which can provide accurate measurements of mass but are less successful measuring radius. Planets observed via a number of different methods therefore can be most accurately compared to Earth.\n\n==Similarity of non-planets to Earth==\n\n[[File:Io, Earth & Moon size comparison.jpg|thumb|The Moon, Io and Earth shown to scale. Although significantly smaller, some of the Solar System's moons and dwarf planets share similarities to Earth's density and temperature.]]\nThe index can be calculated for objects other than planets, including [[natural satellite]]s, [[dwarf planet]]s and [[asteroid]]s. The lower average density and temperature of these objects give them lower index values. Only [[Titan (moon)|Titan]] (a moon of Saturn) is known to hold on to a significant atmosphere despite an overall lower size and density. While [[Io (moon)|Io]] (a moon of Jupiter) has a low average temperature, surface temperature on the moon varies wildly due to geologic activity.<ref>{{cite journal |title=New estimates for Io eruption temperatures: Implications for the interior |journal=Icarus |last=Keszthelyi |first=L. |display-authors=etal |pages=491\u2013502 |volume=192 |issue=2 |date=2007 |doi=10.1016/j.icarus.2007.07.008 |bibcode=2007Icar..192..491K|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1259031 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Earth analog]]\n* [[Exoplanetology]]\n* [[List of potentially habitable exoplanets]]\n* [[Superhabitable planet]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://phl.upr.edu/projects/habitable-exoplanets-catalog/data HEC: Data of Potential Habitable Exoplanets and Exomoons]\n* [http://www.fxsolver.com/browse/formulas/Earth+Similarity+Index Earth Similarity Index calculator]\n\n{{Exoplanet}}\n[[Category:Exoplanetology]]\n[[Category:Exoplanets]]\n[[Category:Planetary science]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Terrestrial planet sizes.jpg|thumb|510x510px|Though differing in size and temperature, terrestrial planets of the Solar System tend to have high Earth Similarity Index values \u2013 [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]] (0.596), [[Venus]] (0.444), [[Earth]] (1.00) and [[Mars]] (0.697){{cn|date=August 2019}}. Sizes to scale.<ref name=\"UPR-Catalog\">{{Cite web|url = http://phl.upr.edu/projects/habitable-exoplanets-catalog/data|title = HEC: Data of Potential Habitable Worlds}}</ref>]]\nThe '''Earth Similarity Index''' ('''ESI''') is a proposed characterization of how similar a [[planetary-mass object]] or [[natural satellite]] is to [[Earth]].  It was designed to be a scale from zero to one, with Earth having a value of one; this is meant to simplify planet comparisons from large databases. It has no quantitative meaning for [[Planetary habitability|habitability]].\n\n== Formulation ==\nThe ESI, as proposed in 2011 by Schulze-Makuch ''et al.'' in the journal [[Astrobiology (journal)|''Astrobiology'']]'','' incorporates a planet's [[radius]], [[density]], [[escape velocity]], and [[Planetary equilibrium temperature|surface temperature]] into the index.<ref name=\"Schulze-Makuch et al.\">{{cite journal |author=Schulze-Makuch, D. |author2=M\u00e9ndez, A. |author3=Fair\u00e9n, A. G. |author4=von Paris, P. |author5=Turse, C. |author6=Boyer, G. |author7= Davila, A. F. |author8=Resendes de Sousa Ant\u00f3nio, M. |author9=Catling, D. |author10=Irwin, L. N. |last-author-amp=yes |date=2011 |doi=10.1089/ast.2010.0592 |bibcode=2011AsBio..11.1041S |title=A Two-Tiered Approach to Assess the Habitability of Exoplanets. |journal=Astrobiology |volume=11 |issue=10 |pages=1041\u20131052 |pmid=22017274}}</ref> Thus the authors describe the index as having two components: (1) associated with the interior which is associated with the mean radius and bulk density, and (2) associated with the surface which is associated with the escape velocity and surface temperature. An article on the [[preprint server]] [[arxiv.org]] attempts to reproduce the ESI using only the temperature and [[Planetary mass|mass]] of the planet.<ref name=\"Chandra\">{{cite arXiv|eprint=1507.06293v1|class=astro-ph.EP|author=Suresh Chandra|author2=Subas Nepal|title=Earth Similarity Index with two free parameters|date=July 2015|author3=Mohit K. Sharma}}<!-- pages=2-4 --></ref> ESI was also referenced in an article published in ''[[Revista Cubana de F\u00edsica]]''.<ref name=\"Gonzalez\">{{cite journal|year=2013|title=Possibilities of life around Alpha Centauri B.|arxiv=1401.2211|journal=Revista Cubana de F\u00edsica|volume=30|issue=2|page=81|author=Gonzalez, A.|author2=Cardenas, R.|author3=Hearnshaw, J.|last-author-amp=yes|bibcode = 2014arXiv1401.2211G }}</ref>\n\nFor [[exoplanet]]s, in almost every case only the planet's [[orbital period]] along with either the [[transit method|proportional dimming of the star due to the planet's transit]] or the [[radial velocity method|radial velocity variation of the star]] in response to the planet is known with any degree of certainty, and so every other property not directly determined by those measurements is speculative. For example, while surface temperature is influenced by a variety of factors including [[irradiance]], [[tidal heating]], [[albedo]], [[insolation]] and [[greenhouse warming]], as these factors are not known for any exoplanet, quoted ESI values use [[planetary equilibrium temperature]] as a stand-in.<ref name=\"Schulze-Makuch et al.\" />\n\nA webpage maintained by one of the authors of the 2011 ''Astrobiology'' article, Abel M\u00e9ndez at the [[University of Puerto Rico at Arecibo]], lists his calculations of the index for various exoplanetary systems.<ref name=esi>{{cite web|title=Earth Similarity Index (ESI)|url=http://phl.upr.edu/projects/earth-similarity-index-esi|publisher=Planetary Habitability Laboratory}}</ref> M\u00e9ndez's ESI is calculated as\n\n:<math>\\mathsf{ESI} = \\prod_{i=1}^{n}\\left(1-\\Big\\vert\\frac{x_i - x_{i0}}{x_i + x_{i0}}\\Big\\vert\\right)^\\frac{w_i}{n}</math>,\n\nwhere <math>x_i</math> and <math>x_{i0}</math> are properties of the extraterrestrial body and of Earth, respectively, <math>w_i</math> is the weighted exponent of each property, and <math>n</math> is the total number of properties. It is comparable to, and constructed from, the [[Bray\u2013Curtis dissimilarity|Bray\u2013Curtis Similarity Index]].<ref name=esi /><ref name=\"Rushby\">{{cite journal|author=Rushby, A.|year=2013|title=A multiplicity of worlds: Other habitable planets|journal=Significance|volume=10|issue=5|pages=11\u201315|doi=10.1111/j.1740-9713.2013.00690.x}}</ref> The weight assigned to each property, <math>w_i</math>, are [[free parameter]]s that can be chosen to emphasize certain characteristics over others or to obtain desired index thresholds or rankings. The webpage also ranks what it describes as the habitability of planets and moons according to three criteria: the location in the habitable zone, ESI, and a speculation as to a capacity to sustain organisms at the bottom of the food chain, a different index collated on the webpage identified as the \"Global Primary Habitability scale\".<ref name=\"Sample\">{{cite news|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2011/dec/05/habitable-exoplanets-catalogue-alien-life|title=Habitable exoplanets catalogue ranks alien worlds on suitability for life.|author=Sample, I.|date=December 5, 2011|accessdate=April 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe 2011 ''Astrobiology'' article and the ESI values found in it received press attention at the time of the article's  publication. As a result, [[Mars]] was reported to have the second-highest ESI in the Solar System with a value of 0.70.<ref name=\"BBC\" />  A number of [[exoplanet]]s listed in that article were reported to have values in excess of this, with [[Teegarden b]] reported to have the highest ESI<ref name=\"Armstrong\" /> of [[Exoplanet#Confirmed discoveries|confirmed]] exoplanets at 0.95.\n\nOther ESI values that have been reported by third parties include:<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|title=Most liveable alien worlds ranked|date=November 23, 2011|accessdate=April 10, 2016|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-15863549|publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref><ref name=esi />\n\nIn next table, planets marked with * represents unconfirmed planet or planet candidate. Distances are from Earth Star system.\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Planet || ESI || Distance ([[Light-year|ly]]) || Notes\n|-\n| Earth || {{ESIScore |esi=1.00}} || 0 ||\n|-\n|[[KOI-4878.01]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.98}} ||1075\n|unconfirmed but surface pressure may be 10[[Atmosphere_(unit)|atm]] at 292K, G4V-type Sun-like star\n|-\n|[[TRAPPIST-1e]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.95}} || 40 ||likely [[Tidal locking|tidally locked]] to star, surface pressure may be as little as 6[[Atmosphere_(unit)|atm]] at 285K, one of the most habitable known planets\n|-\n|[[Teegarden b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.95}} || 12 ||\n|-\n|[[Gliese 581 g]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.92}} || 20 ||unconfirmed, [[Tidal locking|tidally locked]] to star, surface pressure may be 18[[Atmosphere_(unit)|atm]] at 284K\n|-\n|[[Luyten b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.91}} || 12.2 ||[[Tidal locking|tidally locked]] to star, surface pressure may be 25[[Atmosphere_(unit)|atm]] at 294K\n|-\n|[[TRAPPIST-1 d]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.91}} || 40 ||innermost habitable planet in TRAPPIST-1 system\n|-\n|[[Kepler-438b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.88}} || 640 ||temperature 276 K, likely [[Tidal locking|tidally locked]], habitability is uncertain\n|-\n|[[Proxima Centauri b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.87}} || 4.2 ||closest potentially habitable planet\n|-\n|[[Ross 128 b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.86}} || 11 ||host star is inactive and quiet, it is habitable if has an Earth-like atmosphere\n|-\n|[[LHS 1723|LHS 1723 b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.86}} || 17.5 ||lack of planet density or atmospheric data \n|-\n|[[Kepler-296 e]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.85}} || ||\n|-\n|[[Gliese 667 Cc]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.85}} || 23.62 ||likely [[Tidal locking|tidally locked]]  to star, temperature is 277.4 K (4.3\u00b0C), based on black body temperature calculation\n|-\n|[[Kepler-442b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.84}} || 1206 ||it is in center of the habitable zone, temperature 233 K\n|-\n|[[Kepler-452b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.83}} || 1402 ||surface pressure may be 16-56[[Atmosphere_(unit)|atm]] at 288K with [[Breathing gas|Helium]] if strong [[Absorption spectroscopy|587.5nm line]].\n|- \n|[[Kepler-62e]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.83}} || 1200 ||surface pressure may be 35[[Atmosphere_(unit)|atm]] at 288K with [[Breathing gas|Helium]] if strong [[Absorption spectroscopy|587.5nm line]].\n|-  \n|[[Gliese 832 c]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.81}} || 16 ||[[Tidal locking|tidally locked]], no [[plate tectonics]], it is habitable if have an Earth-like atmosphere \n|-\n|[[Kepler-283c]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.79}} || ||temperature is 238.5 K\n|-\n|[[HD 85512 b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.77}} || 36 || if has an Earth-like atmosphere, without [[greenhouse effect]]\n|-\n|[[Wolf 1061c]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.76}} || 13.8 || \n|-\n|[[Gliese 667 Cf]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.76}} || 23.6 ||controversial existence\n|-\n|[[Kepler-440b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.75}} || 850 ||it has an elliptical orbit, temperature 273 K \n|-\n|[[HD 40307 g]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.74}} || 42 ||  \n|-\n|[[Mars]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.73}} ||  ||lacks global [[plate tectonics]], too small for [[Atmospheric escape|atmospheric water vapour]]\n|-\n|[[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.73}} || ||in 3:2 [[Orbital resonance|spin-orbital resonance]] to [[Sun]]\n|-\n|[[Kepler-61b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.73}} || 1100 || \n|-\n|[[Gliese 581 d]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.72}} || 20.4 ||[[Tidal locking|tidally locked]] to star\n|-\n|[[Kepler-22b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.71}} || 587 ||  \n|-\n|[[Kepler-443b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.71}} || 2540 ||it has 89.9% chance of habitability, yet only 4.3% to be rocky\n|-\n|[[Gliese 422 b]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.71}} || ||unconfirmed\n|-\n|[[TRAPPIST-1 f]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.70}} || 39 ||temperature is 230 K, small chance to be rocky\n|-\n|[[Gliese 3293 c]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.70}} || ||unconfirmed\n|-\n|[[Kepler-62f]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.69}} || 990 ||surface pressure may be 10[[Atmosphere_(unit)|atm]] at 288K with [[Breathing gas|Helium]] if strong [[Absorption spectroscopy|587.5nm line]]\n|-\n|[[Teegarden c]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.68}} || 12 ||  \n|-\n|[[Kepler-298d]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.68}} || 1545 ||  \n|-\n|[[Kapteyn b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.67}} || 12.8 ||oldest known potentially habitable planet \n|-\n|[[Kepler-186f]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.64}} || 582 ||potentially colder climate than Mars, but still habitable planet\n|-\n|[[Kepler-174d]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.61}} || \n|-\n|[[Kepler-296f]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.60}} || \n|-\n|[[Gliese 667 Ce]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.60}} || 23.6 ||controversial existence\n|-\n|[[HD 69830 d]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.60}} || 40.7 ||lack of planet density or atmospheric data\n|-\n|[[TRAPPIST-1 g]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.59}} || 39 ||largest planet in system, too cold to be habitable \n|-\n|[[Gliese 682 c]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.59}} ||  ||unconfirmed \n|-\n|[[55 Cancri c|55 Cnc c]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.56}} ||  ||lack of planet density or atmospheric data\n|-\n|[[Moon]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.56}} ||  ||too small for surface or [[Atmospheric escape|atmospheric water]], lacks [[plate tectonics]]\n|-\n|[[55 Cancri f|55 Cnc f]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.53}} || 41 ||lack of planet density or atmospheric data\n|-\n|[[KOI-4427b]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.52}} ||  ||unconfirmed\n|-\n|[[Gliese 581b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.48}} || ||it orbits within inner edge of habitable zone\n|-\n|[[Venus]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.44}} || ||solar [[Radiant flux|flux]] > [[Komabayasi-Ingersoll limit]], [[Retrograde and prograde motion|slow retrograde orbit]] induced by [[Sun]].\n|-\n|[[Kepler-20f]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.44}} || 929 || \n|-\n|[[Gliese 1214b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.42}} || 48 ||it is probably ocean planet, temperature 390-552 K\n|-\n|[[Kepler-11b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.30}} || || \n|-\n|[[Kepler-20e]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.29}} || || \n|-\n|[[Mu Arae e]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.27}} || || \n|-\n|[[Gliese 581 c]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.24}} || 20.37 ||[[Tidal locking|tidally locked]] to star\n|-\n|[[Kepler-20b]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.24}} || || \n|-\n|[[Neptune (planet)|Neptune]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.18}} || ||Gas giant, blue color\n|-\n|[[Gliese 581 e]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.16}} || 20.4 ||[[Tidal locking|tidally locked]] to star\n|-\n|[[Jupiter (planet)|Jupiter]] || {{ESIScore |esi=0.12}} || ||Gas giant\n|-\n|[[KOI-55c]]* || {{ESIScore |esi=0.03}} || || \n|-\n|}\n\n==No relation to habitability==\nAlthough the ESI does not characterize [[planetary habitability|habitability]], given the point of reference is the Earth, some of its functions match those used by habitability measures. As with the definition of the [[habitable zone]], the ESI uses surface temperature as a primary function (and the terrestrial point of reference).  A 2016 article uses ESI as a target selection scheme and obtains results showing that the ESI has little relation to the habitability of an exoplanet, as it takes no account of the [[Flare star|activity of the star]], planetary [[tidal locking]], nor the planet's [[magnetosphere|magnetic field]] (i.e. ability to protect itself) which are among the keys to habitable surface conditions.<ref name=\"Armstrong\">{{cite journal |title=The host stars of Kepler's habitable exoplanets: superflares, rotation and activity |author=Armstrong, D. J. |author2=Pugh, C. E. |author3=Broomhall, A.-M. |author4=Brown, D. J. A. |author5=Lund, M. N. |author6=Osborn, H. P. |author7=Pollacco, D. L. |journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society |volume=5 |issue=3 |year=2016 |doi=10.1093/mnras/stv2419 |bibcode=2016MNRAS.455.3110A |arxiv=1511.05306 |pages=3110\u20133125}}</ref>\n\nIt has been noted that ESI fails to differentiate between [[Earth]] similarity and [[Venus]] similarity, as can be seen in the table above, where planets with a lower ESI have a greater chance at habitability<ref name=\"Tasker\">{{cite news|title=No, that new exoplanet is not the best candidate to support life|url=https://theconversation.com/no-that-new-exoplanet-is-not-the-best-candidate-to-support-life-28996|author=Elizabeth Tasker|date=July 9, 2014|publisher=[[The Conversation]]|accessdate=November 5, 2018}}</ref>.\n\n==Planets with an Earth-like size==\n\n[[File:Relative sizes of all of the habitable-zone planets discovered to date alongside Earth.jpg|thumb|Comparison of the sizes of planets [[Kepler-69c]], [[Kepler-62e]] (0.83), [[Kepler-62f]] (0.69), and the [[Earth]]. All planets except the Earth are artists' conceptions.]] \nThe classification of exoplanets is difficult in that many methods of exoplanet detection leave several features unknown. For example, with the [[transit method]], one of the more successful measurement of radius can be highly accurate, but mass and density are often estimated. Likewise with [[radial velocity]] methods, which can provide accurate measurements of mass but are less successful measuring radius. Planets observed via a number of different methods therefore can be most accurately compared to Earth.\n\n==Similarity of non-planets to Earth==\n\n[[File:Io, Earth & Moon size comparison.jpg|thumb|The Moon, Io and Earth shown to scale. Although significantly smaller, some of the Solar System's moons and dwarf planets share similarities to Earth's density and temperature.]]\nThe index can be calculated for objects other than planets, including [[natural satellite]]s, [[dwarf planet]]s and [[asteroid]]s. The lower average density and temperature of these objects give them lower index values. Only [[Titan (moon)|Titan]] (a moon of Saturn) is known to hold on to a significant atmosphere despite an overall lower size and density. While [[Io (moon)|Io]] (a moon of Jupiter) has a low average temperature, surface temperature on the moon varies wildly due to geologic activity.<ref>{{cite journal |title=New estimates for Io eruption temperatures: Implications for the interior |journal=Icarus |last=Keszthelyi |first=L. |display-authors=etal |pages=491\u2013502 |volume=192 |issue=2 |date=2007 |doi=10.1016/j.icarus.2007.07.008 |bibcode=2007Icar..192..491K|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1259031 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Earth analog]]\n* [[Exoplanetology]]\n* [[List of potentially habitable exoplanets]]\n* [[Superhabitable planet]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://phl.upr.edu/projects/habitable-exoplanets-catalog/data HEC: Data of Potential Habitable Exoplanets and Exomoons]\n* [http://www.fxsolver.com/browse